fe of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":70,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth Tibetot was born in 1385, in Cambridgeshire, England, her father, Sir Payne Tibetot, was 32 and her mother, Agnes Wroth, was 30. She married John Daneys about 1410. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1385–":"1385–Surnud","1370–1443":"1370–1443","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1390–1424":"1390–1424","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1410–1491":"1410–1491","1353–1413":"1353–1413","1355–1413":"1355–1413","1385":"1385","1491":"1491","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","abt 1410":"umbes 1410","1413":"1413","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","1443":"1443","1375":"1375","1353":"1353","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1385–":"